This student will explore the atmospheric conditions that accompany dust devil formation by combining the vortex catalog with environmental measurements from the MEDA RDS dataset. For each detected vortex, they will extract variables such as air temperature, ground temperature, wind speed, wind direction, humidity, and pressure, then compare these conditions to periods when no vortices were observed. The goal is to determine whether dust devils preferentially occur under specific environmental conditions and to identify the factors that may promote vortex formation. This project introduces the student to planetary meteorology, environmental data analysis, and hypothesis testing while providing a pathway toward understanding the physical drivers of dust devil activity at Jezero Crater.

Big Question
"What atmospheric conditions favor dust devil formation?"
This uses your RDS data.
